Overall, social protection spending levels were inversely associated with tuberculosis prevalence, incidence, and mortality. For a country spending 0% of their GDP on social protection, moving to spending 1% of their GDP was associated with a change of −18·33 per 100 000 people (95% CI −32·10 to −4·60; p=0·009) in prevalence, −8·16 per 100 000 people (−16·00 to −0·27; p=0·043) in incidence, and −5·48 per 100 000 people (−9·34 to −1·62; p=0·006) in mortality. This association was mitigated at higher levels of social protection spending, and lost significance when more than 11% of GDP was spent.
